The paper deals with the problem of exact pattern matching in labeled graphs, which is a fundamental problem in graph algorithms and has applications in computational biology, graph databases, and graph mining. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) are likely sub-categories. The paper also mentions graph databases and heterogeneous networks, which suggests cs.DB (Databases) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses a lower bound based on the Strong Exponential Time Hypothesis (SETH), which is a topic in computational complexity theory, making cs.LG (Logic in Computer Science) a possible sub-category as well.
